<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910221-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>910221-0085.</DOCID><HL>   REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:   Punchdrunk</HL><DATE>02/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   AFRIC RD SC LABOR</CO><IN>OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><LP>   Apartheid is being dismantled in South Africa, and NewJersey Governor Jim Florio decided to act. &quot;Now is no time tolet up,&quot; he says. &quot;As a former boxer, I understand whenyou've got a guy on the ropes you don't stop punching.&quot;   So Governor Florio decided that Shell Oil will have toclose its gas stations on the New Jersey Turnpike. SinceRoyal/Dutch Shell continues to operate in South Africa, theUnited Mine Workers of America has summoned a boycott,declaring Shell the &quot;worst corporate collaborator with theapartheid regime.&quot; With nothing else to worry about excepthis tax policy, his school policy, his insurance policy, hissoaring unpopularity and a bill to deregulate smoking, thepugnacious Governor couldn't pass up a good fight.</LP><TEXT/></DOC>